WEBVTT

00:00:02.720 --> 00:00:05.440
Coast is on
its biggest expedition ever.

00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:22.320
After exploring Britain
and Europe for eight years,

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:25.640
we've hopped hemispheres
to an extraordinary continent.

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:33.040
It's the furthest that Coast
has ever travelled.

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:39.960
We've come to a land
so majestic and so massive,

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:41.520
it's breath-taking.

00:00:42.280 --> 00:00:45.360
And makes me wonder,
why I haven't been here before.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:48.880
But now, I can finally say...

00:00:49.720 --> 00:00:52.360
This is Coast Australia.

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:03.760
It's a country,
an island and a continent.

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:08.200
Blessed with over 60,000 kilometres
for us to explore

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:10.640
on our greatest adventure yet.

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:23.520
For some,
this is what Australia is all about.

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:26.480
Fantastic beaches, shimmering sands,

00:01:26.600 --> 00:01:29.440
fabulous coral reefs
and exotic marine life.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:34.520
But that would be a disservice to
this vast and fascinating continent

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:37.320
with the sixth
longest coastline in the world

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:40.000
and a history of humankind
that stretches back

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:42.040
at least 50,000 years.

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:53.400
Australia is 30 times
bigger than Britain.

00:01:53.880 --> 00:01:55.720
The Great Barrier Reef alone

00:01:56.120 --> 00:01:58.800
is spread over a larger area
than the UK.

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:02.480
The scale is astonishing.

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:06.440
So it's little wonder
most Australians

00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:08.440
proudly huddle by the coast,

00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:11.640
magnetically drawn by the splendour,

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:14.600
the opportunity and the lifestyle.

00:02:16.480 --> 00:02:19.840
Our task is to capture
the dazzling diversity

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:23.200
of this young, modern nation
but ancient land

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:25.880
as we discover the secrets,
the scenery,

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:28.080
and the stories of its people.

00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:34.160
With such an epic canvas,
you might ask, where do we start?

00:02:35.360 --> 00:02:37.800
From the Kimberley,
the series features stories

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:39.280
in seven other regions.

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:42.400
Darwin and beyond,
the Great Barrier Reef,

00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:46.440
The Gold to Sunshine Coast,
Sydney, Victoria,

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:48.840
Tasmania, and the Coral Coast.

00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:52.720
I've gathered a team of experts

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:55.160
who will take us
on this exciting journey.

00:02:56.840 --> 00:03:00.480
Writer, palaeontologist
and an Australian of the year,

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:03.760
Professor Tim Flannery,
is peerless in his knowledge

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:06.520
of the history and formation
of the continent.

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:10.240
Marine ecologist, Dr Emma Johnston,

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:12.600
a New South Wales
Scientist of the Year,

00:03:12.680 --> 00:03:16.680
explores the stunning biodiversity
of Australian waters.

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:19.960
Anthropologist, Dr Xanthe Mallett,

00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:23.840
uses her forensic experience
to unravel stories of the past.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.000
Landscape Architect, Brendan Moar,
is passionate about

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:31.960
the geography of the shoreline,
and the folks who call it home.

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:36.800
And Miriam Corowa, journalist
and saltwater woman herself,

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.360
investigates the social evolution
of this dynamic coast.

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:47.160
And as for me?
Well, I get the job of a lifetime,

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:49.240
because I get to be your guide

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:52.800
and with 80 percent of Australians
living on the coastline

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:56.120
and so many stories to be told,
I'd better get cracking.

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:22.160
For Coast Australia's
inaugural journey,

00:04:22.240 --> 00:04:25.600
we're in one of the world's
last great wilderness areas,

00:04:26.680 --> 00:04:30.480
the Kimberley in the north-west
corner of the continent

00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:33.120
where the first humans
may have arrived from Asia

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:35.400
a long, long time ago.

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:38.800
There's been
a rich coastal culture, here,

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:41.200
for at least the last 50,000 years.

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:45.560
A way of life
that was once embedded in the rocks

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:47.600
and the land of this coastline.

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:51.080
At the very least,
it's now a repository of knowledge

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:53.440
for those who still live here today.

00:04:53.920 --> 00:04:56.560
Best of all for me,
this stretch of coastline

00:04:56.640 --> 00:04:58.960
has many places associated
with the dreaming,

00:04:59.240 --> 00:05:02.160
and we'll be visiting
a few of them along the way.

00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:11.640
Joining me in this episode,
Tim Flannery trips over dinosaurs.

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:14.360
And there
is a pink dinosaur foot.

00:05:15.520 --> 00:05:19.320
Xanthe Mallett explores
a unique maritime war grave.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:21.680
This is a raft.

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:24.840
If we do see a crocodile
or a shark, do we have a safe word?

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:27.840
Brendan Moar takes to water
on an ancient raft.

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:32.760
Emma Johnston dishes up the mud
on migratory shorebirds.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:38.000
And I investigate
Broome's glittering place in history.

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:41.240
Look at that. It's like Jupiter
compared to the Earth.

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:44.960
This is the Kimberley Coast.

00:06:10.960 --> 00:06:14.720
Our journey stretches
from Eighty Mile Beach in the west,

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:17.960
through Broome,
around the Dampier Peninsula

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:22.240
and across the Buccaneer Archipelago
to Freshwater Cove.

00:06:25.080 --> 00:06:27.320
The Kimberley region
of Western Australia,

00:06:27.400 --> 00:06:29.800
is three times the size of England,

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:32.600
with a population
of just 40,000 souls.

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:35.680
So, with so few people
per square kilometre,

00:06:35.880 --> 00:06:39.480
it's one of the most sparsely
populated regions on planet Earth.

00:06:40.120 --> 00:06:41.600
And so when it comes
to getting around,

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:43.160
one of these is very useful.

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:55.960
Remote and rugged,
this is a land where time began.

00:06:57.200 --> 00:07:01.680
Ancient gorges and deep fjords,
fan out to magnificent bays

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:06.200
dotted with primeval monoliths
endless horizons everywhere.

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:13.000
I have to say, in all my travels,
this is some of the wildest,

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:17.040
most edge-of-the-world-feeling
coastline, I think I've ever seen.

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:21.400
There's also a very
strong feeling from it

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:24.240
that if you were to have been here
200 years ago,

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:25.920
or even 2000 years ago,

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:28.840
it would've looked just the same.

00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:49.640
This is a landscape
that dwarfs humanity.

00:07:51.080 --> 00:07:52.800
At four billion years,

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:56.200
Australia features some
of the oldest land forms on Earth,

00:07:56.800 --> 00:07:59.920
which means an endless
cornucopia of history

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:02.160
for Palaeontologist, Tim Flannery,

00:08:02.240 --> 00:08:05.720
who's stepping back in time
to walk with dinosaurs.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:17.360
Do you know what's
really special about this place?

00:08:17.680 --> 00:08:21.120
A hundred million years ago
when these rocks were laid down,

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:24.080
India was just over there.

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:29.440
I'm walking along
what's known as the Dinosaur Coast

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:32.320
on the Dampier Peninsula,
just north of Broome.

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:41.840
Palaeontologists have recorded
at least 15 types of dinosaur

00:08:41.920 --> 00:08:43.480
that roamed this area,

00:08:43.560 --> 00:08:46.280
leaving literally
thousands of tracks and trackways.

00:08:47.680 --> 00:08:49.760
I'm really lucky to get to see these,

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:52.720
because they're only exposed
at a very low tide,

00:08:52.800 --> 00:08:56.200
for a few hours,
for a very few days every year.

00:08:57.600 --> 00:09:00.520
Dr Steve Salisbury
is a palaeontologist

00:09:00.600 --> 00:09:03.800
with a special interest
in the biomechanics of dinosaurs

00:09:03.880 --> 00:09:06.200
how they're shaped and move.

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:08.880
- So what have we got here?
- Dinosaur footprint.

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:11.600
I've walked over hundreds
of those coming to meet you.

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:14.880
- You probably have.
- So, Steve, I think I can see,

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:18.160
maybe some toes here, is that--
Am I looking at it right?

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:22.040
Yeah, so it's a three-toe track.
So there's one, two, three.

00:09:22.160 --> 00:09:26.240
That's the back of the footprint,
so he's headed that way.

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:29.280
So what would this dinosaur
look like you reckon?

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:31.680
Well, the reason
we're interested in this one

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:35.960
is because this looks like tracks
that in Spain and Portugal,

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:40.040
and then also North America,
have been attributed to Stegosaurs.

00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:41.800
Right.
So Stegosaurs are the guys

00:09:41.880 --> 00:09:43.400
with the big plates on the back.

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:44.560
That's right.

00:09:47.800 --> 00:09:50.640
With the help of traditional
custodian, Richard Hunter,

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:53.000
and research assistant, Nigel Clarke,

00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:56.280
Steve is going to make
a silicon cast of the footprint

00:09:56.360 --> 00:09:58.280
for further museum studies.

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:02.760
So, Steve, how did these
tracks form? And why right here?

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.040
Well, 130 million years ago,

00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:09.120
this was part of a big floodplain
heading out probably into a delta.

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:13.840
Back then, Australia was still
part of the Gondwana supercontinent

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:17.160
that included South America,
Africa and India

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:21.080
Here, periodic floods
would have deposited

00:10:21.160 --> 00:10:24.840
layers of mud on the sandbars
that made up the floodplain,

00:10:24.920 --> 00:10:28.120
which was bordered by dense forests
of cycads and ferns.

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:34.080
Dinosaurs roamed the boggy terrain
leaving their imprints everywhere.

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:38.240
Usually, the muddy prints
would have dried up and crumbled away

00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:42.000
but on the Dinosaur Coast,
blankets of sand covered them

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:45.040
and preserved them,
a fossilised landscape.

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:49.120
So, for instance, here,

00:10:49.280 --> 00:10:52.120
this bigger one,
you can see this is his big toe,

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:56.000
that's the second toe, and then
the third, fourth and the fifth,

00:10:56.080 --> 00:10:57.600
and then there's the small track

00:10:57.680 --> 00:11:00.440
of a bipedal ornithopod dinosaur
that's overprinted it.

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:01.840
So, Sauropod.

00:11:01.920 --> 00:11:04.480
Great, big long neck, long tail,
one of the classic dinosaurs.

00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:07.360
Yeah, yeah. Brachiosaurus
or Diplodocus that kind of thing.

00:11:07.960 --> 00:11:09.880
Footprints form all the time.

00:11:09.960 --> 00:11:12.520
We left a trail of them on the beach
when we walked down here,

00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:15.400
but rarely do they get preserved
in the fossil record.

00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:18.120
It's an incredible diversity
of dinosaurs.

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:20.920
Like there's not really
anywhere else in the world

00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:24.520
that has such a level of diversity
represented by tracks.

00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:26.280
Comes away quite cleanly,
doesn't it?

00:11:26.360 --> 00:11:27.760
Yeah.

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:33.960
And there
is a pink dinosaur foot...

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:35.720
...of all things!

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:40.320
Today's science teaches us
about our geophysical beginnings

00:11:40.720 --> 00:11:43.240
but there's a much older account
that emanates

00:11:43.360 --> 00:11:46.240
from the coast's
indigenous Goolarabooroo people.

00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:50.680
Richard has a fascinating
and very different reading

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:52.160
of these ancient tracks...

00:11:54.240 --> 00:11:56.560
...a Dreamtime story of Emu Man.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.040
The first ancestral spirit
that walked the Earth

00:12:13.040 --> 00:12:14.920
So, what's the name of that Emu Man?

00:12:17.360 --> 00:12:19.440
- Marella. Okay. Yeah.
- Marella, yeah.

00:12:19.600 --> 00:12:22.680
And did he bring something
to the land when he came?

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:28.960
To Richard and his people,

00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:31.160
Marella gave the knowledge
through songs,

00:12:31.680 --> 00:12:34.040
which are akin to oral heritage maps.

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:36.640
Laws to sustain balance

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:39.320
and well-being of the land
and its people,

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:42.080
and passed
down through the generations.

00:12:51.680 --> 00:12:54.600
You know, plenty of Australia's
coastline's spectacular,

00:12:54.840 --> 00:12:56.600
but there's nothing like this.

00:12:56.960 --> 00:13:00.400
Price's Point is just unique
because it brings together

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.560
Aboriginal Australia
and European Australia

00:13:04.760 --> 00:13:07.320
in a way that no other place
on the continent does.

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:10.560
It's the origin of the Dreamtime
for Aboriginal people

00:13:10.640 --> 00:13:12.400
across a great swathe
of the continent,

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:15.840
and for European people,
it's an incredible repository

00:13:15.960 --> 00:13:18.200
of ancient knowledge,
a vanished world.

00:13:32.880 --> 00:13:35.640
The Kimberley weathers
two distinct seasons

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:38.640
a searing dry and the surging wet...

00:13:39.160 --> 00:13:42.760
which floods the rivers and bays
that divide the rugged plateaus.

00:13:43.320 --> 00:13:49.160
It's a dramatic wilderness
sculpted by time, pressure and water.

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:54.000
The Kimberley region
has the greatest tidal range

00:13:54.080 --> 00:13:56.360
in the whole
of the southern hemisphere.

00:13:56.520 --> 00:13:59.520
And the second highest
in the entire world.

00:14:03.600 --> 00:14:06.000
The 12-metre tidal change, here,

00:14:06.080 --> 00:14:08.360
is magnified
by the shape of the coast.

00:14:09.160 --> 00:14:13.840
The currents increase considerably to
squeeze huge volumes of tidal water

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:17.360
in and out of the bays and rivers
through narrow gaps.

00:14:18.360 --> 00:14:21.960
I'm going to discover how
this stunning coastline was formed

00:14:22.040 --> 00:14:24.320
with the help
of a quick geology lesson

00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:27.320
and then,
wrestle with that surging tide

00:14:27.480 --> 00:14:30.360
at one of the greatest
natural wonders of the Kimberley,

00:14:30.840 --> 00:14:33.960
the Horizontal Waterfalls
in Talbot Bay.

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:43.760
All right. Thank you.

00:14:44.080 --> 00:14:46.200
Geologist, Dr lan Tyler,

00:14:46.280 --> 00:14:49.240
has written the book
on this serene emerald setting.

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:51.800
- This is an interesting spot.
- It is indeed.

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:56.880
This sandbox shows
how two continental masses collided

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.520
to create this stunning
billion-year-old vista.

00:15:01.040 --> 00:15:05.160
We're compressing five million years
probably into several minutes.

00:15:05.240 --> 00:15:08.680
The Horizontal Falls
are in this bit of the model.

00:15:08.760 --> 00:15:11.160
The creation of folds and thrusts,

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:14.560
that make up the crumpled geology
of Talbot Bay.

00:15:20.480 --> 00:15:22.880
When that was buckled like a rug

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:25.840
pushed up by an opening door,
that was solid?

00:15:25.920 --> 00:15:28.520
It wasn't... It's not
pushing in sand. It's folding rock.

00:15:28.600 --> 00:15:32.240
It was old enough to be
solid rock when that happened.

00:15:32.360 --> 00:15:34.840
So, the pressure is enough

00:15:34.920 --> 00:15:37.440
and is held for a long enough time

00:15:37.520 --> 00:15:41.560
that it starts to flow like toffee.

00:15:45.920 --> 00:15:47.960
Right, now that I've had
my geology lesson,

00:15:48.040 --> 00:15:50.400
it's time to see
the Horizontal Falls up close.

00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:52.440
Hi there.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.320
Right, so tell me, Adrian,
what's happening here?

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:07.160
Well, basically it's what
you call a tidal pinch.

00:16:07.480 --> 00:16:09.760
The tide's actually rising faster

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:11.960
in this bay than it is
in the next bay over.

00:16:12.080 --> 00:16:14.240
The gaps are pinching
how much water

00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:17.000
it'll let through
so we actually go downhill.

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:20.600
I think it's risen today about
nine metres in the last six hours,

00:16:20.680 --> 00:16:23.880
at one hell of a lot of water moving
through there at the moment.

00:16:23.960 --> 00:16:26.400
It peaks at about a million litres
in a second.

00:16:26.480 --> 00:16:29.360
The reason it can do that
is it's not a normal rapid.

00:16:29.440 --> 00:16:32.320
It's not say fast water going
over the top of shallow rocks

00:16:32.400 --> 00:16:35.440
it's extremely deep,
50 metres of water underneath it.

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:37.160
- So, it's like--
- 50 metres deep!

00:16:37.240 --> 00:16:40.880
50 metres deep, so it's like a column
of water powering through there.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:49.560
Time to run the first gauntlet
the 20-metre seaward facing gap.

00:16:57.040 --> 00:16:59.240
That was relatively sedate.

00:16:59.560 --> 00:17:03.240
And now, onto a smaller
more powerful boat

00:17:03.600 --> 00:17:05.680
and the narrower ten-metre gap.

00:17:05.760 --> 00:17:07.320
The water speed
we're doing at the moment,

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:09.280
about 30 kilometres an hour

00:17:09.400 --> 00:17:11.640
just sitting holding the boat
here still.

00:17:11.720 --> 00:17:14.760
The sounder's reading 44 metres.

00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:19.160
- So it's about 150 feet of water
- Yeah, underneath us, yeah.

00:17:19.240 --> 00:17:22.000
- And we should be moving forward
- Yeah, yep.

00:17:22.080 --> 00:17:24.400
- At 30 kilometres.
- Yeah.

00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:28.000
I've got the boat, you know,
probably 600 horse power,

00:17:28.800 --> 00:17:30.960
third throttle
just holding us still here.

00:17:31.040 --> 00:17:34.080
It's like an ocean trying
to get through a letterbox.

00:17:34.160 --> 00:17:35.640
- Isn't it?
- Yeah, absolutely.

00:17:59.240 --> 00:18:01.120
I was a little bit alarmed there!

00:18:02.200 --> 00:18:04.480
The boat feels
completely inconsequential.

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:06.080
It just gets flung through,

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:09.160
and then it hits something,
and it's like hitting a brick wall.

00:18:15.840 --> 00:18:17.120
What was that?

00:18:19.320 --> 00:18:21.920
- Pretty rough, ain't it?
- It's amazing, a powerful stuff.

00:18:38.480 --> 00:18:40.360
The stunning colours
of Australia

00:18:40.440 --> 00:18:43.000
are most vivid
along the Kimberley Coastline.

00:18:43.680 --> 00:18:46.960
Ochre sandstone cliffs,
red pindan sand

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:50.560
folding into the turquoise waters
of Broome's Roebuck Bay.

00:18:51.160 --> 00:18:52.680
It's a unique setting.

00:18:53.080 --> 00:18:56.000
But as Anthropologist
Dr Xanthe Mallet discovers,

00:18:56.240 --> 00:18:59.760
seventy years ago,
this tranquil vista was shattered

00:18:59.840 --> 00:19:02.320
when the war
spilled over to Australia.

00:19:08.760 --> 00:19:10.680
By early 1942,

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:13.360
the Japanese were
pushing through Indonesia

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:15.880
or the Dutch East Indies
as it was known then.

00:19:19.160 --> 00:19:22.680
In a rush to escape, Allied military
planes were commissioned

00:19:22.760 --> 00:19:26.520
to evacuate Dutch refugees
from their colonial homes in Java.

00:19:28.560 --> 00:19:32.720
A fleet of flying boats, Catalinas,
Dorniers and Short Empires

00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:35.800
carrying families
and their few precious belongings

00:19:35.880 --> 00:19:38.120
took flight for Australia's
main cities.

00:19:39.160 --> 00:19:43.040
On the 2nd of March, they landed
in Broome's Roebuck Bay to refuel.

00:19:45.840 --> 00:19:48.000
Given the area's large tidal movement

00:19:48.080 --> 00:19:51.560
and the lack of facilities to ferry
more than a hundred refugees

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:54.000
to and from the small port town,

00:19:54.080 --> 00:19:56.600
the passengers stayed
on board for the night.

00:19:57.800 --> 00:20:01.880
At 9:20 AM the next morning,
nine Japanese Zeroes appeared

00:20:01.960 --> 00:20:04.040
and couldn't believe their luck.

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:07.440
Before them,
15 flying boats lay at anchor

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:12.080
each with 30 or more Dutch refugees,
mostly women and children.

00:20:13.040 --> 00:20:16.080
With no Allied resistance,
the Zeroes opened fire,

00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:20.200
strafing the flying boats repeatedly
before turning to the airfield

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:23.160
and destroying
a further seven military aircraft.

00:20:27.320 --> 00:20:29.080
In a vain attempt to save them,

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:31.920
parents threw their children
into the water

00:20:32.280 --> 00:20:34.960
only to see it set alight
by burning fuel.

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:39.880
Many who didn't die in the attack,
were incinerated or drowned

00:20:39.960 --> 00:20:42.920
as they attempted to swim
the kilometre back to shore.

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:46.320
It was a harrowing massacre
that lasted an hour,

00:20:46.480 --> 00:20:49.920
but lingers on today
in the mudflats of Roebuck Bay.

00:20:54.440 --> 00:20:57.080
And I'm going
to follow the tide out to see

00:20:57.160 --> 00:20:58.880
the dramatic evidence for myself.

00:21:02.480 --> 00:21:06.560
I'll be heading out with aviation
archaeologist, Dr Silvano Jung,

00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:08.400
who's been studying Roebuck Bay's

00:21:08.480 --> 00:21:11.120
unique maritime museum
for two decades.

00:21:12.920 --> 00:21:16.640
They're the first aircraft wrecks
to be heritage-listed in Australia.

00:21:16.760 --> 00:21:21.000
And they're only exposed at a king
low tide for a few days of the year.

00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:23.320
So which one is this?

00:21:23.560 --> 00:21:25.040
This is the X-23.

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:28.200
It was Sir Rudolf Idzerda's
Dornier flying boat.

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:31.520
There was only one person on board
at the time it was lost.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:33.720
And he's still missing.

00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:38.000
There are six exposed at low tide

00:21:38.120 --> 00:21:40.200
and there's another nine
in deep water.

00:21:40.320 --> 00:21:41.880
So nine you've never seen?

00:21:41.960 --> 00:21:45.240
I've seen four of them
but there's still five missing.

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:48.600
So, this was more exposed?

00:21:48.720 --> 00:21:51.120
Yeah, well it was exposed right down
to the keel...

00:21:51.200 --> 00:21:52.800
- Was it?
- ...ten years ago.

00:21:53.120 --> 00:21:55.440
Silvano has been
surveying the wreck site

00:21:55.520 --> 00:21:58.360
and returns every ten years
to record the changes.

00:21:59.600 --> 00:22:01.360
We're just gonna
take a photograph

00:22:01.480 --> 00:22:03.840
of the bow section to show

00:22:03.920 --> 00:22:05.840
the amount of sedimentation
over time.

00:22:06.120 --> 00:22:08.320
- Yeah.
- Can you just set up this scale?

00:22:08.400 --> 00:22:10.560
- Where do you want it?
- Just over here, I think.

00:22:10.640 --> 00:22:11.960
- Right.
- On this side.

00:22:12.960 --> 00:22:14.880
Why is it important to document it?

00:22:15.600 --> 00:22:18.880
This is one of the most
significant sites in Australia.

00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:21.040
There's like a battlefield here

00:22:21.760 --> 00:22:25.480
so it's documenting rare flying boats
in a way that--

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:28.840
so they will--
We'll never see these aircraft again.

00:22:31.320 --> 00:22:33.880
It's very important
that they remain in situ,

00:22:33.960 --> 00:22:38.480
and it's the best conservation
measure, to do nothing.

00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:39.680
- Yeah.
- In a way.

00:22:39.760 --> 00:22:42.600
But it also feels more appropriate
that they stay here.

00:22:47.520 --> 00:22:50.840
As there were no accurate
records of passenger numbers,

00:22:50.920 --> 00:22:54.600
we'll never know exactly
how many people lost their lives

00:22:54.840 --> 00:22:57.480
but Silvano estimates
more than a hundred.

00:22:57.960 --> 00:23:00.880
Husbands, mothers and children...

00:23:01.400 --> 00:23:04.560
Ghosts swirling in the eddies
of Roebuck Bay,

00:23:04.720 --> 00:23:06.920
while the survivors
live with the memories

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.200
of war's deathly embrace.

00:23:17.280 --> 00:23:22.240
With just 15,000 residents,
Broome is the Kimberley's big town.

00:23:22.360 --> 00:23:26.320
It was built on pearling, a story
that can be told in two parts.

00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:29.800
In the beginning
it was all about the shell.

00:23:32.640 --> 00:23:35.280
I've come here to investigate
how the humble oyster

00:23:35.360 --> 00:23:37.240
has come to define Broome

00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:40.280
and its glittering place
in Australia's history.

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:45.600
By the turn of the 19th century,

00:23:45.680 --> 00:23:48.640
this modest settlement
had global currency,

00:23:49.040 --> 00:23:51.640
thanks to a coastline replete
with one of nature's

00:23:51.840 --> 00:23:53.480
most beautiful shells.

00:23:55.720 --> 00:23:58.160
This is Pinctada Maxima.

00:23:58.880 --> 00:24:02.200
And it was buttons like this,
made from the mother of pearl

00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:06.080
that made this material
so valuable in the 1800s.

00:24:06.880 --> 00:24:09.480
But the Broome
pearling industry story

00:24:09.600 --> 00:24:11.600
began much earlier than that.

00:24:14.360 --> 00:24:19.120
Pearl oysters were noted here during
the voyage of the Beagle in 1839.

00:24:19.800 --> 00:24:21.800
But it wasn't until the 1860s,

00:24:21.920 --> 00:24:24.200
when colonists noticed
Aboriginal people

00:24:24.280 --> 00:24:27.320
wearing and trading the distinctive
mother-of-pearl shell,

00:24:27.480 --> 00:24:31.400
that the industry grew to supply
international demand for buttons,

00:24:31.480 --> 00:24:34.640
knife handles
and fascias for wristwatches.

00:24:38.280 --> 00:24:42.320
The settlers didn't just acknowledge
that ancient indigenous custom,

00:24:42.600 --> 00:24:44.360
they enslaved Aborigines

00:24:44.480 --> 00:24:47.800
and worked them ruthlessly
to harvest the shell in earnest.

00:24:50.440 --> 00:24:51.760
This statue is a reminder

00:24:51.840 --> 00:24:55.000
of the very worst form
of the exploitation.

00:24:56.040 --> 00:25:00.600
It often involved kidnapping.
It almost always involved slavery.

00:25:01.200 --> 00:25:03.760
Aboriginal girls were forced to dive

00:25:04.400 --> 00:25:06.200
with no kit whatsoever,

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:09.240
naked and with no air supply.

00:25:09.880 --> 00:25:13.320
Unbelievably,
it was often pregnant girls

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:15.760
because the belief
was that pregnant girls

00:25:15.840 --> 00:25:17.680
had greater lung capacity

00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:20.080
and so could hold
their breath for longer.

00:25:22.960 --> 00:25:25.120
When slave trading,
or "blackbirding",

00:25:25.200 --> 00:25:27.000
was outlawed in 1869,

00:25:27.440 --> 00:25:30.320
Broome had to find others
to dive for shell.

00:25:30.880 --> 00:25:35.600
In 1901, the White Australia Policy
restricted non-white immigration

00:25:36.200 --> 00:25:38.440
but Broome, which, by 1910,

00:25:38.520 --> 00:25:40.960
was the world's largest
pearl shell centre,

00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:42.840
was given a special exemption.

00:25:43.840 --> 00:25:47.240
Over the coming decades,
Asian and Islander immigrants

00:25:47.320 --> 00:25:50.920
arrived to work in what was still
a very difficult business.

00:25:53.160 --> 00:25:55.040
With a history of their own
in pearling,

00:25:55.120 --> 00:25:58.120
Japanese divers were targeted
as the most skilled.

00:25:58.360 --> 00:26:00.960
And so began
a long association with Broome.

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:06.640
Itsushi Shioji came here
as a deckhand in 1966.

00:26:07.480 --> 00:26:09.160
How dangerous was it?

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:29.120
It was the vulcanised canvas suits

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:31.800
topped by copper helmets,
or "hard hats",

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:35.160
and lead-weighted boots,
introduced by the Japanese,

00:26:35.280 --> 00:26:37.480
that assured their place
in the industry.

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:41.880
To get a wee taste
of all that hard history,

00:26:41.960 --> 00:26:43.680
I'm going to try it on.

00:26:44.200 --> 00:26:46.600
Looking at what's involved
in suiting up,

00:26:46.840 --> 00:26:49.280
diving might have been the easy part.

00:26:50.800 --> 00:26:53.560
Very natty Shetland wool stockings.

00:26:58.360 --> 00:26:59.840
Shetland wool Jumper.

00:27:04.360 --> 00:27:07.400
Made from fine Scottish
traveling rugs by the look of things.

00:27:09.120 --> 00:27:10.880
This is how I dress at home you know.

00:27:12.240 --> 00:27:13.720
Do you know what this is for?

00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:16.400
I'll leave the rest
to your imagination.

00:27:16.480 --> 00:27:18.280
I can promise you
there's not much to see.

00:27:18.360 --> 00:27:20.600
These are all the rage
in Carnaby street at the moment.

00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:26.320
This is a cushion to take the weight.

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:29.840
Feels great.

00:27:31.640 --> 00:27:34.120
So if you imagine
that a typical Japanese diver

00:27:35.160 --> 00:27:39.160
in real life in his vest and pants,
probably weighed about 60 kilos.

00:27:40.120 --> 00:27:43.080
On the seabed
when he was fully togged up,

00:27:43.480 --> 00:27:46.280
you can make that about 180 kilos,

00:27:46.600 --> 00:27:50.200
lumbering about in all of this
for hours at a time.

00:27:52.160 --> 00:27:55.840
The arrival of plastic buttons
soon after WWII

00:27:55.920 --> 00:27:57.760
killed the pearl shell business.

00:27:59.600 --> 00:28:04.120
But in the mid-1950s, the industry
was revitalised by cultured pearls

00:28:04.360 --> 00:28:06.480
which is Broome's story today.

00:28:20.760 --> 00:28:24.600
Under a cobalt sky
and above a sapphire sea,

00:28:25.120 --> 00:28:26.520
it feels like I'm traveling

00:28:26.600 --> 00:28:29.280
beyond the furthest reaches
of any known map.

00:28:32.920 --> 00:28:35.040
I'm cruising through
the pristine waters

00:28:35.120 --> 00:28:36.800
of the Buccaneer Archipelago,

00:28:37.320 --> 00:28:39.560
off the tip of the Dampier Peninsula,

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:43.680
to find out how to grow or culture
a perfect pearl.

00:28:46.440 --> 00:28:49.800
By the early 1900s,
Broome's pearl shell industry

00:28:49.880 --> 00:28:52.320
was supplying 80 percent
of the world's demand

00:28:52.400 --> 00:28:53.960
for buttons and textiles.

00:28:54.360 --> 00:28:57.800
In 1946, a local man, Dean Brown,

00:28:57.920 --> 00:29:01.640
decided to head further north
to wild, unchartered territory

00:29:01.720 --> 00:29:03.000
in search of fresh beds

00:29:03.080 --> 00:29:06.400
of the Kimberley's renowned
Pinctada Maxima shell.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:08.680
Fortune favoured the brave.

00:29:08.960 --> 00:29:12.840
The prize was abundant shell
in King Sound's sheltered waters,

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:16.720
shallow reefs and the protected
harbour of Cygnet Bay.

00:29:16.960 --> 00:29:20.520
But Dean Brown was still in it
for shells not pearls,

00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:23.080
as grandson James Brown tells me.

00:29:23.280 --> 00:29:24.560
- How you doing?
- G'day, Neil.

00:29:24.640 --> 00:29:27.720
He wouldn't have had the faintest
idea about cultured pearls.

00:29:27.800 --> 00:29:32.760
It was a secret that was held by
the Japanese and only used in Japan.

00:29:33.120 --> 00:29:36.680
And it wasn't until ten years later,

00:29:36.760 --> 00:29:39.960
that that technology
started coming to Australia.

00:29:40.240 --> 00:29:43.120
And how did he go
about making the transition then

00:29:43.200 --> 00:29:45.800
from just harvesting
the natural shell

00:29:46.160 --> 00:29:48.920
to thinking about setting up a farm?

00:29:49.320 --> 00:29:51.880
He got the insight
when the Japanese

00:29:52.240 --> 00:29:54.200
started running Kuri Bay

00:29:54.480 --> 00:29:56.760
and that was
an American owned company.

00:29:56.880 --> 00:29:59.280
My grandfather ended up
running the supplies up

00:29:59.360 --> 00:30:01.400
- for that pearling company.
- Was that nearby?

00:30:01.720 --> 00:30:04.360
It was about 200 kilometres
further up the coast.

00:30:05.120 --> 00:30:08.000
He managed to convince my uncle
that it was a good idea

00:30:08.080 --> 00:30:11.200
that he come up
and try some experiments.

00:30:11.280 --> 00:30:14.080
And so, as a young 20-year-old,
my uncle did that

00:30:14.200 --> 00:30:18.280
and miraculously succeeded
and to this day,

00:30:18.360 --> 00:30:21.720
he's acknowledged as the first
non-Japanese person in the world

00:30:21.800 --> 00:30:24.960
to figure out how to culture pearls
and then to do it commercially.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.880
Three generations later,
and the Brown family

00:30:29.960 --> 00:30:32.640
is still cultivating pearls
at Cygnet Bay,

00:30:33.200 --> 00:30:35.520
the oldest pearl farm in Australia.

00:30:35.880 --> 00:30:39.400
I think I imagined that the oysters
would just be left out here doing

00:30:39.520 --> 00:30:43.760
whatever oysters do but it turns out,
they need regular maintenance.

00:30:46.440 --> 00:30:50.120
The farm's 50,000 shells
are cleaned once a month

00:30:50.200 --> 00:30:54.080
of marine weed and barnacles which
hamper the oysters' ability to feed.

00:30:54.760 --> 00:30:58.720
Pinctada Maxima grows larger
than other pearl oyster species

00:30:58.880 --> 00:31:01.600
which means
potentially bigger pearls.

00:31:02.520 --> 00:31:06.720
The natural lives of these oysters
are heavily influenced by science.

00:31:07.600 --> 00:31:10.560
Right, okay.
It's like a biology class.

00:31:10.640 --> 00:31:11.880
Absolutely.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:14.520
What would happen naturally,
in one of these big shells

00:31:14.600 --> 00:31:17.360
if it was just living
its normal seabed life,

00:31:17.920 --> 00:31:19.920
that would cause it to create a pearl

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:21.880
without any interference
from a farmer?

00:31:21.960 --> 00:31:24.000
There's a range of things
that can do it,

00:31:24.080 --> 00:31:26.960
but generally,
it's almost an immune response,

00:31:27.040 --> 00:31:30.160
so something irritates it
and it can't get rid of it.

00:31:30.240 --> 00:31:31.960
So like a grain of sand or whatever?

00:31:32.040 --> 00:31:34.240
Or a little bit of a crab claw
might get in there,

00:31:34.320 --> 00:31:35.960
or a worm might bore through

00:31:36.400 --> 00:31:39.120
so the animal will start
laying nacre down around it.

00:31:39.240 --> 00:31:42.480
So, wherever a little grain
of sand went in, say it landed there,

00:31:42.640 --> 00:31:45.200
that mantle would start to lay down

00:31:45.280 --> 00:31:49.480
more of this shiny shell around it
to make it smooth.

00:31:49.560 --> 00:31:51.080
Yeah, you're absolutely right.

00:31:51.960 --> 00:31:55.240
Culturing pearls means
that we introduce the irritant

00:31:55.320 --> 00:31:59.360
into the oyster in the form of
a small ball shaped from shells,

00:31:59.440 --> 00:32:03.000
which the oyster then coats
with its silvery white substance

00:32:03.080 --> 00:32:06.960
called nacre to produce
a lustrous, round pearl.

00:32:07.280 --> 00:32:08.360
Hopefully!

00:32:09.120 --> 00:32:11.400
Okay, Neil. Are you ready
to harvest your first pearl?

00:32:11.520 --> 00:32:12.960
- Okay.
- Take a seat.

00:32:14.960 --> 00:32:17.320
Now, bring the shell up.
Put it on the stand.

00:32:17.920 --> 00:32:20.400
Put that edge in.

00:32:24.720 --> 00:32:27.120
Now I can't feel it.

00:32:27.560 --> 00:32:29.600
- I've lost the baby's head!
- No.

00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:33.160
Two years of hard work
by the oyster, and...

00:32:34.360 --> 00:32:36.440
- Look at that
- JAMES: Well done.

00:32:36.520 --> 00:32:38.000
That's like
a little bit of magic,

00:32:38.080 --> 00:32:39.920
that's like
the most elaborately wrapped...

00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:41.720
birthday present, ever.

00:32:43.480 --> 00:32:45.800
Look! A little jewel of the sea.

00:32:46.680 --> 00:32:50.320
After 50 years of trialling
and working,

00:32:50.640 --> 00:32:53.080
this is what we've managed
to come up with.

00:32:53.760 --> 00:32:56.440
Wow.

00:32:56.640 --> 00:32:58.640
Right, okay. Now what is that?

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:02.240
That's the world's largest
fine quality round pearl.

00:33:02.320 --> 00:33:05.160
22.2 millimetres.

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:08.600
Look at that. It's like Jupiter
compared to the Earth.

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:09.520
Yeah.

00:33:09.760 --> 00:33:12.680
So how much is this one worth,
would you say?

00:33:12.760 --> 00:33:14.320
That'd be worth
a couple hundred dollars

00:33:14.400 --> 00:33:15.920
once it's set into a jewellery piece.

00:33:16.160 --> 00:33:17.320
And the grand-daddy?

00:33:17.400 --> 00:33:19.720
Well, that's possibly
a couple of million dollars.

00:33:20.200 --> 00:33:21.400
My goodness.

00:33:23.360 --> 00:33:24.720
Not bad for a mollusc.

00:33:34.280 --> 00:33:37.640
Sharing the Dampier Peninsula,
just east of Cygnet Bay,

00:33:37.760 --> 00:33:39.720
One Arm Point is home

00:33:39.800 --> 00:33:42.440
to the saltwater Bardi people
of the Kimberley.

00:33:42.840 --> 00:33:46.000
This is old Australia,
where tribal knowledge

00:33:46.080 --> 00:33:50.520
has evolved from the natural cycles
of the earth, particularly the tide,

00:33:50.880 --> 00:33:52.640
which has brought Brendan Moar here

00:33:52.720 --> 00:33:54.920
to discover how people
used to get around,

00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:58.520
before the arrival of boats
and outboard motors.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:05.480
These waters are well known
for their huge tidal movements.

00:34:05.880 --> 00:34:09.520
Tides up to 12 metres flow
through this bay every single day.

00:34:09.880 --> 00:34:12.400
It's a fact that the traditional
owners of this land

00:34:12.480 --> 00:34:14.240
acknowledge and respect.

00:34:20.040 --> 00:34:22.840
The local Bardi people
used the power of the tides

00:34:22.920 --> 00:34:24.440
to move around the coast.

00:34:27.040 --> 00:34:29.440
I'm meeting Bardi tribesman,
Albert Wiggan,

00:34:29.560 --> 00:34:31.280
who's going to show me
how they did that

00:34:31.400 --> 00:34:33.480
and hopefully
catch some dinner, too!

00:34:33.560 --> 00:34:35.360
Welcome, welcome to our country.

00:34:35.440 --> 00:34:37.680
Thank you.
It is absolutely stunning.

00:34:38.280 --> 00:34:40.480
This water is something else.

00:34:40.880 --> 00:34:42.600
Well, this is One Arm Point,
you know?

00:34:42.680 --> 00:34:44.880
This is the land of the Bardi people.

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:49.600
We're gonna go and make a raft
and finishing a raft

00:34:49.680 --> 00:34:53.120
and I'll basically show you how,
in a traditional way,

00:34:53.200 --> 00:34:56.080
the old people used to navigate,
you know, using the tides.

00:34:56.200 --> 00:34:58.760
What inspired the Bardi people
to actually build the raft?

00:34:58.840 --> 00:35:01.680
If you look just straight down here.
I mean, this is the foam.

00:35:01.800 --> 00:35:05.120
The foam sort of inspired the idea
of the raft because it just...

00:35:05.400 --> 00:35:08.160
floats on the surface, right?
There's no sort of restriction.

00:35:08.240 --> 00:35:11.640
There's no sort of friction there
between the water movement underneath

00:35:12.040 --> 00:35:15.120
and the raft itself,
because the raft is virtually

00:35:15.200 --> 00:35:17.680
just gliding over the surface
of the water.

00:35:21.080 --> 00:35:24.680
All right, Brendan.
Here's the other half, mate.

00:35:24.800 --> 00:35:26.600
Right, so this is it.

00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:29.800
Basically, this is what you've got,
right? This is the raft.

00:35:30.040 --> 00:35:32.240
Tell me about the design.
It looks pretty simple,

00:35:32.320 --> 00:35:34.480
but I'm sure that there's more
than meets the eye there.

00:35:34.560 --> 00:35:36.880
Obviously,
it's about buoyancy, you know?

00:35:36.960 --> 00:35:40.240
And obviously, the thicker areas
are going to be more buoyant

00:35:40.360 --> 00:35:42.160
than obviously, the skinny part.

00:35:42.640 --> 00:35:46.600
So, the principal is to combine
both skinny ends

00:35:47.360 --> 00:35:50.720
so that the two fat ends
are floating. You know?

00:35:51.240 --> 00:35:54.160
If we do see a crocodile or a shark,
do we have a safe word?

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.920
No. I'll just push you off.
As long as you know how to swim!

00:35:59.120 --> 00:36:01.320
I'm just gonna get rid of this.
I reckon.

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:03.920
I'm not gonna have much use for that.

00:36:04.520 --> 00:36:07.400
- Mate.
- Now I am a white dugong, right?

00:36:08.720 --> 00:36:11.440
Yeah. Look, I reckon-- Yep.
You sit somewhere around here.

00:36:11.520 --> 00:36:13.960
I'll get up the front
and we'll just see how we go.

00:36:14.040 --> 00:36:17.480
Good luck? You know how to swim,
that's the main thing.

00:36:17.560 --> 00:36:19.160
As long as you know
how to swim, mate.

00:36:19.240 --> 00:36:20.760
Should it go down this much?

00:36:20.840 --> 00:36:21.800
Not really.

00:36:21.920 --> 00:36:23.440
You're right.

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:26.000
Like you said, you're
the white dugong, so you're right.

00:36:26.080 --> 00:36:27.720
I am the big white dugong.

00:36:27.800 --> 00:36:29.920
- All right. Let's go.
- What's the plan?

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:31.280
Where are we going and doing?

00:36:31.360 --> 00:36:34.400
We're gonna head straight
over to that sand bar over there.

00:36:34.520 --> 00:36:36.320
There's a nice little
fishing spot over there.

00:36:36.400 --> 00:36:38.480
There's a fair distance
between here and there.

00:36:38.560 --> 00:36:40.120
Yeah, it's a good workout, mate.

00:36:40.200 --> 00:36:42.880
Keep you fit. Find half an hour
a day, they reckon.

00:36:49.480 --> 00:36:52.360
It was designed purely
and simply because of the tides.

00:36:52.440 --> 00:36:54.640
The main reason was,
obviously, transportation

00:36:54.720 --> 00:36:57.520
but, obviously,
it became the main hunting tool.

00:37:01.400 --> 00:37:04.720
The Bardi people have been
living in and around One Arm Point

00:37:04.840 --> 00:37:06.640
since the last Ice age.

00:37:07.040 --> 00:37:09.160
The sea has been central
to their lives

00:37:09.240 --> 00:37:12.200
as a source of food
and spiritual significance.

00:37:12.960 --> 00:37:15.280
And that's basically
why I build the raft, you know?

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:18.080
That's why I teach people
how to make spears and stuff,

00:37:18.160 --> 00:37:21.360
and my children, you know?
Because I feel that's the legacy

00:37:21.440 --> 00:37:24.320
that our elders pass onto
us young people, you know?

00:37:24.400 --> 00:37:27.280
All this culture,
and it's just really...

00:37:27.720 --> 00:37:30.240
It's all you really need, you know?
It's our identity.

00:37:30.920 --> 00:37:32.520
I wouldn't sell it for the world.

00:37:32.600 --> 00:37:34.160
If only I could stand here.

00:37:34.240 --> 00:37:35.960
Paddle! Paddle boy!

00:37:37.400 --> 00:37:39.960
Yeah, one of these fishes,
we're gonna catch some crocodiles.

00:37:40.400 --> 00:37:43.280
So, like the foam
that inspired the idea

00:37:43.520 --> 00:37:45.760
we've floated gently
over to a fishing spot

00:37:45.840 --> 00:37:47.480
on the other side of the bay...

00:37:48.560 --> 00:37:50.240
to spear ourselves some dinner.

00:38:19.400 --> 00:38:21.560
Spending time
on the Dampier Peninsula,

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:24.800
you get that overwhelming sense
of just how beautiful

00:38:24.880 --> 00:38:26.600
the Australian coastline can be.

00:38:26.960 --> 00:38:29.320
How pristine it is
and how much of it

00:38:29.400 --> 00:38:31.720
has this innate sense
of spirituality.

00:38:32.520 --> 00:38:36.320
So much so, that this place
is truly timeless.

00:38:41.480 --> 00:38:43.720
Well, there you go, mate.
That's dinner.

00:38:45.400 --> 00:38:47.320
Can't get any more fresher than that.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:50.920
I wanna know.
Is it just too good to be true?

00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:53.160
Like how much of this life is left?

00:38:53.480 --> 00:38:56.680
It's up to us as Indigenous
people, you know, how much is left.

00:38:56.760 --> 00:39:00.080
And so, as long as there are people
like me who feel really strong

00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:03.880
and proud about being,
you know, an Aboriginal.

00:39:04.160 --> 00:39:07.880
As long as we are alive, I think
our culture will always stay alive.

00:39:09.560 --> 00:39:12.600
A coast that glimmers
with beauty and spirit.

00:39:24.680 --> 00:39:27.440
Two hundred and fifty kilometres
south-west of Broome,

00:39:27.800 --> 00:39:30.800
another golden crescent
seemingly runs forever.

00:39:31.840 --> 00:39:34.520
The splendid remoteness
of Eighty Mile Beach

00:39:34.680 --> 00:39:36.920
is a haven for nature's migrants.

00:39:39.240 --> 00:39:42.280
Marine Ecologist, Dr Emma Johnston
has travelled

00:39:42.360 --> 00:39:44.520
to this newly declared marine park

00:39:44.600 --> 00:39:48.200
to explore why this area
is a world-famous stomping ground

00:39:48.280 --> 00:39:51.160
for some of the planet's
most adventurous travellers.

00:39:54.280 --> 00:39:58.520
Every year, around half-a-million
migratory shorebirds

00:39:58.800 --> 00:40:00.720
descend on Eighty Mile Beach

00:40:00.800 --> 00:40:03.200
from their breeding grounds
in the Arctic Circle.

00:40:14.360 --> 00:40:18.200
Amongst a variety of shore birds,
these great knots arrive here

00:40:18.320 --> 00:40:21.160
in enormous
whimsical clouds every year

00:40:21.360 --> 00:40:24.560
after an epic
8,000-kilometre journey.

00:40:26.800 --> 00:40:30.400
Dr Jutta Leyrer is part
of the Global Flyway Network,

00:40:30.600 --> 00:40:33.440
a scientific organisation
that studies the ecology

00:40:33.520 --> 00:40:35.200
of migratory shorebirds.

00:40:35.640 --> 00:40:39.160
They would have arrived here
in about October, November,

00:40:39.240 --> 00:40:42.800
pretty much exhausted
after a long trip from Siberia.

00:40:43.400 --> 00:40:46.280
They would have changed their
feathers. They're pretty much worn

00:40:46.360 --> 00:40:49.720
after thousands of kilometres,
non-stop migration.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:54.840
And then by sort of February,
they start to put on body mass again.

00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:01.560
As a secluded marine reserve,

00:41:01.760 --> 00:41:04.480
this is one of the world's
richest foraging grounds.

00:41:04.880 --> 00:41:09.000
The birds feed undisturbed
along the vast tidal mudflats

00:41:09.440 --> 00:41:12.000
on snails, crabs and worms.

00:41:12.080 --> 00:41:16.080
Long thin bristle worms.
Socolicy, sort of made these tubes.

00:41:17.760 --> 00:41:19.600
Now that is good bird food.

00:41:19.760 --> 00:41:21.720
That definitely is good bird food.

00:41:23.720 --> 00:41:25.880
How much do they need
to feed when they come here?

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:29.000
A lot. They basically
double their body weight

00:41:29.080 --> 00:41:31.960
in three, to four, to five weeks.

00:41:34.880 --> 00:41:38.960
Mudflats are ocean meadows
with invisible pastures.

00:41:39.400 --> 00:41:43.440
Every day, the tide comes in
bringing nutrients that feed

00:41:43.760 --> 00:41:47.400
tiny microscopic bacteria
and phytoplankton

00:41:47.480 --> 00:41:49.480
on the surface of these sediments.

00:41:49.800 --> 00:41:52.560
This is rich, nutritious food

00:41:52.840 --> 00:41:55.480
for the invertebrates
that hide beneath.

00:41:57.480 --> 00:41:59.520
So, this is a type of marine snail.

00:42:00.520 --> 00:42:03.920
The snails are eating the bird poo.
The birds are eating the snails,

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:07.560
there's fish in the middle
and it's such a productive ecosystem.

00:42:14.960 --> 00:42:19.080
Refreshed and replenished
by this abundant strip of coast,

00:42:19.320 --> 00:42:23.280
come April, the flocks take flight
for their arduous journey north

00:42:23.520 --> 00:42:25.560
to summer in Siberia.

00:42:32.560 --> 00:42:35.640
I'm flying north too
but only a couple of hours

00:42:35.800 --> 00:42:39.360
from Broome to a special place
a window to the Dreaming,

00:42:39.840 --> 00:42:42.280
the sacred time
in Aboriginal culture,

00:42:42.400 --> 00:42:46.360
when ancestral spirits created
the world and rhythms of life.

00:42:48.200 --> 00:42:52.400
I'm heading to Freshwater Cove
to see some living history...

00:42:54.480 --> 00:42:58.720
the extraordinary restoration
of some very old and sacred artwork.

00:43:02.560 --> 00:43:05.080
I'm really privileged
to be welcomed into this country

00:43:05.160 --> 00:43:08.640
by traditional custodian
and elder, Donny Woologoodja.

00:43:08.920 --> 00:43:11.640
- Welcome to Freshwater Cove.
- Thanks very much.

00:43:13.080 --> 00:43:14.440
It's called Freshwater Cove,

00:43:14.520 --> 00:43:16.560
but what is this place called
in your language?

00:43:28.760 --> 00:43:30.920
We're going
to a very significant place

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:32.760
along this dramatic coastline

00:43:33.120 --> 00:43:35.960
where Donny has to perform
some special maintenance.

00:43:36.600 --> 00:43:39.720
We're heading for Oombri,
or Raft Point.

00:43:47.560 --> 00:43:49.800
I receive a ceremonial marking

00:43:50.080 --> 00:43:53.240
which comes with a Dreamtime story
of two women

00:43:53.480 --> 00:43:55.720
who collected some honey
while hunting.

00:44:12.720 --> 00:44:14.920
And why does it go on my face
when I'm here?

00:44:22.600 --> 00:44:24.080
Okay. Lead on.

00:44:24.520 --> 00:44:28.800
And up we go, accompanied by nephew
and cultural apprentice, Callum,

00:44:28.960 --> 00:44:30.720
along the red earth track.

00:44:31.840 --> 00:44:33.920
The Timor Sea,
a shimmering backdrop...

00:44:35.360 --> 00:44:38.520
and into a primeval art gallery.

00:44:39.600 --> 00:44:41.560
- So, this is the place.
- Yeah.

00:44:41.640 --> 00:44:43.160
- Oombri.
- Yeah.

00:44:44.520 --> 00:44:45.560
Look.

00:44:49.240 --> 00:44:51.200
How long
have those paintings been there?

00:44:51.400 --> 00:44:54.360
Maybe 50,000 years, maybe more.

00:44:59.920 --> 00:45:02.600
What can you tell me
about these figures, Donny?

00:45:02.680 --> 00:45:04.920
Who are they and what do they mean?

00:45:13.880 --> 00:45:15.560
Is there one Wandjina or many?

00:45:21.360 --> 00:45:23.920
So, all of these figures
are Wandjina.

00:45:30.320 --> 00:45:32.320
Why are the Wandjina white?

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:36.800
So they're from the spirit world?

00:45:36.880 --> 00:45:38.560
Yeah. The spirit world, yeah.

00:45:39.080 --> 00:45:42.080
- And then there's obviously fish.
- Yeah, fish, yeah.

00:45:51.240 --> 00:45:53.240
The faces are very, very simple.

00:45:53.320 --> 00:45:56.120
It's just two eyes
and a stroke for a nose.

00:46:06.440 --> 00:46:07.360
Right.

00:46:08.320 --> 00:46:10.160
Following
in his father's footsteps,

00:46:10.280 --> 00:46:12.080
Donny is a senior Worrorra,

00:46:12.160 --> 00:46:15.120
tribal elder,
with a special responsibility

00:46:15.360 --> 00:46:18.440
restoring the Wandjina artwork
to keep it vivid.

00:46:23.800 --> 00:46:27.360
He paints with a profound
sense of respect for his ancestors.

00:46:28.040 --> 00:46:31.800
And for me to witness this,
is a rare privilege indeed.

00:46:39.880 --> 00:46:42.520
Art and spiritual conservation,

00:46:42.600 --> 00:46:45.480
which Donny is training Callum
to assume in time.

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:50.280
First, he has to learn the stories
and then he can touch the art.

00:46:53.040 --> 00:46:55.080
So, an important
part of the people

00:46:55.160 --> 00:46:58.160
coming back to the country,
is to maintain...

00:46:59.040 --> 00:47:00.600
- this.
- Yeah. Yeah.

00:47:07.720 --> 00:47:10.640
You don't need anyone to tell
you that this is a special place.

00:47:11.120 --> 00:47:12.720
It speaks for itself.

00:47:13.400 --> 00:47:16.280
And then you find out that people
have been coming here for

00:47:16.360 --> 00:47:19.520
50,000 years. In fact,
for heaven knows how long.

00:47:20.240 --> 00:47:26.120
And there's definitely a comfort
about realising you're just one

00:47:26.200 --> 00:47:28.480
of a long, long line of people

00:47:28.760 --> 00:47:31.720
who've sat in here
and looked out at the coast.

00:47:38.880 --> 00:47:41.200
To end what has been
a spectacular day

00:47:41.280 --> 00:47:44.080
in this beautiful wilderness,
of Wijingarra Budd Budd,

00:47:44.160 --> 00:47:46.480
I must undergo a farewell ritual.

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:53.720
What does the smoke do?

00:47:55.480 --> 00:47:56.840
Of what?

00:47:56.920 --> 00:47:59.040
- Of the spirits in the cave?
- Yeah.

00:47:59.120 --> 00:48:01.200
So, what would happen
if I wasn't smoked?

00:48:03.480 --> 00:48:04.800
- The spirits?
- Yeah.

00:48:04.880 --> 00:48:07.840
Right, let's get in the smoke!
Do I just step into it?

00:48:07.960 --> 00:48:10.080
Your foot.

00:48:10.680 --> 00:48:12.600
Your foot.

00:48:13.480 --> 00:48:16.560
Your hands. Hands.

00:48:17.600 --> 00:48:20.440
Your head. And you smoke the smoke.

00:48:20.520 --> 00:48:22.720
Then you go... And this one.

00:48:25.880 --> 00:48:29.240
The Wandjina
of Freshwater Cove left their images

00:48:29.400 --> 00:48:32.680
on the cave walls before
they returned to the spirit world.

00:48:33.320 --> 00:48:35.480
And it's the responsibility
of the living,

00:48:35.960 --> 00:48:38.360
Donny, after his father Sam,

00:48:38.960 --> 00:48:41.280
to repaint and maintain those images.

00:48:42.400 --> 00:48:45.360
I've just been cleansed
to make sure I don't take

00:48:45.440 --> 00:48:47.920
any of the spirits with me when I go.

00:48:48.200 --> 00:48:49.560
And I'm glad about that,

00:48:49.640 --> 00:48:52.920
because enough people
have left here over the years,

00:48:53.200 --> 00:48:56.520
and I like the idea
of leaving the spirits behind here

00:48:56.600 --> 00:48:58.800
where they and the people belong.

00:48:58.880 --> 00:49:01.680
# Home sweet home
Home sweet home

00:49:03.120 --> 00:49:06.680
# Home sweet home
Wijingarra Budd Budd

00:49:09.840 --> 00:49:13.320
# Home sweet home
Home sweet home

00:49:13.400 --> 00:49:15.640
# Home sweet home

00:49:16.680 --> 00:49:20.240
# Home sweet home
Wijingarra Budd Budd #

00:49:26.960 --> 00:49:29.600
It's been an incredible
journey through the colours

00:49:29.680 --> 00:49:31.960
and eternal landscapes
of the Kimberley.

00:49:32.320 --> 00:49:35.240
Australia's last great wilderness.

00:49:53.880 --> 00:49:56.080
The Kimberley
is a region of extremes.

00:49:56.400 --> 00:50:00.320
Extreme temperatures,
extreme humidity, even extreme tides.

00:50:01.960 --> 00:50:03.600
It's not for the faint-hearted.

00:50:04.040 --> 00:50:06.880
For some, though,
any hardships or challenges

00:50:07.040 --> 00:50:08.920
are outweighed by the rewards.

00:50:09.280 --> 00:50:12.360
For me, it's definitely a place
best suited

00:50:12.520 --> 00:50:15.000
to those who've adapted to survive.

00:50:17.840 --> 00:50:20.680
Next time,
from remote to radiant.

00:50:20.920 --> 00:50:24.480
The Coast team explores
stunning Sydney Harbour.

00:50:26.040 --> 00:50:29.680
City built on blood sweat,
tears of convicts and oyster shells.

00:50:29.760 --> 00:50:33.360
There was to be no escape.
Or was there?

00:50:33.440 --> 00:50:36.120
Ready, aim, fire!

00:50:37.840 --> 00:50:41.360
What a place to be quarantined.
Feels more like Saint Tropez.

00:50:42.280 --> 00:50:44.440
Look at this underwater garden.

00:50:44.520 --> 00:50:46.640
This little bit there...
That can be Sydney.

00:50:49.080 --> 00:50:51.840
Those stories and more from Sydney.

00:50:52.360 --> 00:50:53.880
Another day in paradise.

